  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What countries can I travel to without an Indian passport?",
  "response": "As an Indian citizen, you typically need a valid passport to travel internationally. However, there are a couple of neighboring countries where you can enter without a passport by using alternative valid identification documents. Here are the main options:\n\n### **1. Nepal**\n- **Requirements:** Indian citizens can enter Nepal without a passport. You can use any of the following valid photo identification documents:\n  - **Aadhaar Card**\n  - **Voter ID Card**\n  - **PAN Card**\n  - **Ration Card**\n  \n- **Travel Details:**\n  - **Entry Points:** Multiple border crossings on both the western and eastern sides of Nepal.\n  - **Duration:** No specific time limit for stay, but it's advisable to carry identification throughout your visit.\n\n### **2. Bhutan**\n- **Requirements:** Similar to Nepal, you can enter Bhutan without a passport using any of the following valid photo IDs:\n  - **Aadhaar Card**\n  - **Voter ID Card**\n  - **PAN Card**\n  - **Ration Card**\n\n- **Travel Details:**\n  - **Entry Points:** Main entry points include Phuentsholing (west), Gelephu (south), and Samdrup Jongkhar (east).\n  - **Visa:** Currently, Indian citizens do not require a visa to enter Bhutan.\n\n### **Additional Information:**\n\n- **Sikkim and Other Special Regions:** If you're traveling within India, regions like Sikkim have specific entry requirements, but they typically don't require a passport for Indian residents.\n\n- **OCI and PIO Cards:** If you hold an Overseas Citizen of India (OCI) or Person of Indian Origin (PIO) card, you may have additional travel privileges to certain countries. However, most international travel will still require a valid passport.\n\n- **Travel to Other Countries:** For travel outside of Nepal and Bhutan, an Indian passport is generally required. Always check the latest visa and entry requirements of the destination country before planning your trip.\n\n### **Key Points to Remember:**\n- **Valid Identification:** Ensure that your alternative ID (like Aadhaar or Voter ID) is valid and not expired.\n- **Carry Multiple IDs:** It's a good practice to carry more than one form of ID when traveling without a passport.\n- **Check Updates:** Travel regulations can change, so always verify the latest requirements from official government sources before traveling.\n\nBy leveraging these provisions, you can conveniently visit Nepal and Bhutan without the immediate need for an Indian passport. For all other international destinations, obtaining a valid passport remains essential.",
